              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Play Styles</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=861"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=861"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=115">Jeremy "jerome" LaMere</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 115 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Some concepts of different play styles.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">I have noticed that there are basically two different playing styles in the Star Wars CCG: playing within your deck and playing within your hand. Some people would argue with me and say that there are more than two different styles, but are you referring to play styles or deck styles that are played? Think about it. In this article I will describe the play styles, compare the play styles, discuss which types of decks are suited to the different play styles, and discuss if the two styles can be combined to make the ultimate playstyle or player.<br>
<br>
This particular concept is something that was discussed between Gabe Alonso and I while he roomed with me at the 1998 World Championships and we were trying to playtest different decks. He is the one that first opened my eyes to this particular concept and explained the basics to me.<br>
<br>
The first play style that I would like to describe is what I call the Alread Style (as in Joe Alread), because this is how he tends to play. This is a style were you play within your hand. Basically what this means is that you draw a few amount of cards and set up what you can with those cards. You then draw up to anywhere between 10 to 15 cards and wait for the opponent to set something up and then you use the cards in your hand to find the best possible solution to the situation that has been presented. And you continue the game by playing with the cards you draw and have available to you. Now you may be saying to yourself, Is this stupid, this is how everyone plays. However, wait until you here the description of the next play style.<br>
<br>
I find the next play style, playing within your deck (Old School), to be more common (although the trend I see happening is a movement to the Alread style or a small combination of the two). This play style uses the entire deck to achieve its goal. If you cant find a card, this play style will draw a huge amount of cards to find the card they need or get a card that can search for the card that they need. And they continue to play the game this way, finding the cards that they need when they need them.<br>
<br>
Now I am not trying to imply that Joe is not an old school player (because he has been to the first 3 world championships), but he plays differently than most old school players. The major difference between the styles, is that with the Old School style you rely more heavily on the cards that are located in your deck while you are playing. By this I mean that if you loose that crucial card from the top of your deck or you keep drawing to find that one card that you believe that can help you win and then you dont find it, it can affect your play. If you have ever played against Alread you know that he does not loose his composure very easily because he makes you feel that he has everything in his hand that he needs. He just sets up a solid foundation then he waits for you to react or setup something so that he can hinder you while he does his thing. A prime example of the old school type player is Mike Girard because he plays decks that use a lot of multiples and combinations and allow cards to let him get what he needs. Maelstrom and Vegas Style are two prime examples of decks that he uses to this effect.<br>
<br>
Old School style tends to pack a lot of multiples so that you can have in your hand what you need when you need it. Cards like Traffic Control/Reactor Terminal, The Signal/Twilek Advisor, etc. are common in players decks that use this style so that they can find what they need and put stuff back that they dont need. Mains and Toys, combo, and Manipulation decks use this type of play style. Also SAC tends to be played by players that use this style. When playing this style you have the tendency to draw huge number of cards, so be careful. First of all you setting yourself up for Grimnock. You have less life force to work with when you have a large hand. And if you are drawing cards, you arent doing anything in the game.<br>
<br>
Alread style decks are more along the lines of Big Blue, Mains and Mofos type decks. A lot of gray matter (guys and ships). Few interrupts and effects are played. Most of the interrupts played by this style are floating high destinies. In my experience this style takes a lot more practice, patience, and skill because you are drawing a small amount of cards so you have to make the best of the situation that you are in with the cards that you have.<br>
<br>
With the introduction of Objectives, the play styles have had the opportunity to flourish and combine into the ultimate play style because a lot of the objectives allow you to start will a large number of cards on the table. They also search for the cards that you need to flip the objective. A prime example is ROps. This deck is advantaged in a player that can use both styles well. During the game you are allowed to search through the deck to find what you need WHILE still drawing a few amount of cards. However, I still see the utilization of the two styles exclusively by players, especially the ones that have been playing since the old days (Premiere and A New Hope). Some players have been able to adapt and overcome.<br>
<br>
The player that most sticks out in my mind is Gabe Alonso. He showed me how to recognize the different styles and he knows when to utilize the different styles. I, to a certain extent have been able to adapt, but I still have a tendency to play within my deck. I feel that once a player can recognize and master the two different styles he can be a very good player because he/she is aware of what is in the deck and is able to play the deck, not let the deck play him/her.<br>
<br>
Well, I hope that I have provided some useful information and explained a little more about playstyles that you may not have thought about before. And perhaps some of you will try to utilize the different styles the next time you play to try and truely recognize the difference between the two.<br>
<br>
Later,<br>
J </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=861"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=861"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=861" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
